# Avoid Unicode Characters in Code

When writing or editing code files, use only ASCII characters. Unicode characters that visually resemble ASCII can cause StrReplace tool failures due to byte-level mismatch.

## Common Problem Characters

- Multiplication sign (U+00D7) - use x or * instead
- Minus sign (U+2212) - use - instead
- Smart quotes (U+2018/2019/201C/201D) - use single or double quote instead
- Ellipsis (U+2026) - use ... instead
- Arrow (U+2192) - use -> instead

## Why This Matters

The StrReplace tool requires exact byte-for-byte matching. If a file contains Unicode multiplication sign but the replacement string uses ASCII x, the match fails with Invalid arguments error.

## Example

```python
# BAD - Unicode multiplication sign (U+00D7)
# Calculate total RF area as median [unicode x] cell count

# GOOD - ASCII characters only
# Calculate total RF area as median x cell count
```

## When Editing Files

1. Read the file first to check for existing non-ASCII characters
2. Use ASCII equivalents in all code and comments
3. If StrReplace fails, check for Unicode using: [c for c in line if ord(c) > 127]
